snippet.textDisplay: didn't see you grease the clutch pivots and throwout bearing. If you lay under the trans there is a clutch shaft with a grease zerk at each bushing where it pivots in the bellhousing. There will be a cover on the bottom of the bellhousing held in with either 5/16 or 3/8 bolts that allows you to look up at the clutch, and you will see a grase zerk at the bottom of the throwout bearing. You only need a few pumps in it to keep it lubed, don't make it gush out or you will sling grease into your clutch discs eventually.

snippet.textDisplay: That cab over truck looks like an antique Boyd Trucking truck from the late 1980'S. 350 Cummins engines were not very powerful. If you modified the engine a little you could make 380 h.p.. If you could find Royal Purple oil additive for deseil engines it would help a whole lot. Rotella oil is best for those old engines. Fuel injectors did clog up on in the engines. Lucas fuel cleaner would help. Brakes adjusters were mostly non self adjusting back then, but they started putting them on. Just tighten them all the way up and back them off 1/3 turn. I recomend you take the drums off and inspect the brake shoes. They might be cracked from sitting for so long and you might find a drum very thin or grooved. Don't forget to change out the hub oil in the axels. Check for axels oil seals leaking. Change the transmission and differential oils. I got to tell you that D.O.T. laws have changed and you need a black box and a computer controlled engine on the road. Now a days those old trucks are illegal. I don't know why.
